PLANT PESTS, NEW DATA, EPPO
***************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
Date: Thu, 25 Nov 1999 21:11:32 est
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Sources: EPPO Secretariat, 1999-06
Review of Agricultural Entomology, 87(7 to 9). Jul-Sep 1999
Review of Plant Pathology, 78(7 to 9). Jul-Sep 1999

99/135 New data on quarantine pests
By browsing through the literature, the EPPO Secretariat has extracted the
following new data concerning quarantine pests. [Edited to remove items on
pests which do not attack major food crops]

New geographical records
------------------------
Citrus blight disease (EU Annexes) is reported to occur in:
- BELIZE (blight-affected trees grafted on sour orange rootstock),
- COSTA RICA (on _Carrizo citrange_ rootstock)
- GUATEMALA(on Rangpur (_Citrus limonia_)rootstock).
Review of Plant Pathology, 78(7), p 643 (4884).
Sinaloa tomato leaf curl begomovirus is reported for the first time in
COSTA RICA . In October 1998, symptoms were commonly observed in tomato
plantings near Turrialba.
Review of Plant Pathology, 78(7), p 630 (4785).
Tomato yellow leaf curl begomovirus (EPPO A2 quarantine pest) is reported
for the first time in REUNION (FRENCH PACIFIC). Symptoms were first
observed in tomato crops in September 1997, on a farm located on the south
coast of the island. A preliminary survey was carried out from December
1997 to April 1998
in both outdoor and protected tomato crops. All infected samples were
collected on the leeward coast.
Review of Plant Pathology, 78(7), p 630(4784).

Detailed records
----------------
Grapevine bois noir phytoplasma was observed in summer 1998 in some
vineyards of Chardonnay planted in 1991, in 2 areas of Molise region, ITALY.
Review of Plant Pathology, 78(7), p 642 (4877).
Stenocarpella maydis (EPPO A2 quarantine pest) is one of the main fungi
isolated from infected maize kernels in Santa Catarina, BRAZIL.
Review of Plant Pathology, 78(8), p 710 (5405).
Tomato spotted wilt tospovirus (EPPO A2 quarantine pest) is present in
Haryana, INDIA, affecting peanut crops.
Review of Plant Pathology, 78(7), p 647 (4914)
Tomato yellow leaf curl begomovirus (EPPO A2 quarantine pest) is reported
on tomato crops in Shizuoka and Aichi prefectures (Honshu), JAPAN.
Review of Plant Pathology, 78(7), p 630 (4787).
Xanthomonas vesicatoria was found in association with tomato spotted wilt
tospovirus (both EPPO A2 quarantine pests) on tomatoes in the states of
Bahia and Pernambuco, BRAZIL.
Review of Plant Pathology, 78(8), p 728(5537).
